	abstract = {Antarctic hyperiid ŽThemisto gaudichaudi, Hyperia macrocephalus, and Primno macropa. and gammarid amphipods Ž Eusirus perdentatus and Orchomene rossi. were collected near Elephant Island, located in the South Shetland Islands, during January and February 1997 and 1998. Polar lipid ŽPL. was the major lipid class in all amphipods Ž58–88\% of total lipid., except for T. gaudichaudi in which triacylglycerol ŽTAG. was dominant Ž62\%.. Cholesterol was the major sterol in the gammarid amphipods Ž89–91\% of total sterols., and the hyperiid P. macropa Ž70\%.. The hyperiids T. gaudichaudi and H. macrocephalus had a more diverse sterol composition including trans-dehydrocholesterol, desmosterol, 24nordehydrocholesterol, 24-methylcholest-5,22 E-dien-3b-ol, 24-methylenecholesterol, and stanols Žmostly cholestanol.. Eicosapentaenoic acid wEPA, 20:5Ž n y 3.x and docosahexaenoic acid wDHA, 22:6Ž n y 3.x were the major polyunsaturated fatty acids ŽPUFA. in all amphipods. The PUFA octadecapentaenoic acid w18:5Ž n y 3.x was not detected in 1997 samples, but comprised 0.3–1.2\% in all 1998 samples. The PUFA 18:4Ž n y 3. comprised 0.2–4.2\% in all samples from both years. Very long chain PUFA ŽVLC-PUFA. ŽC24 and C26. were not detected in the one 1997 sample but comprised 0.6–2.8\% of total fatty acids in almost all 1998 amphipods. Monounsaturated fatty acids included 18:1Ž n y 9.c, 18:1Ž n y 7.c, and 16:1Ž n y 7.c. Principal saturated fatty acids in all amphipods were 16:0, 14:0, and 18:0. Examination of biomarker lipids has helped clarify trophic interactions for these Antarctic amphipods, and revealed annual differences in their food sources. q 2001 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved.},
